         public <T> T newInstance(Class<T> c) throws Exception {
+          if (c.isInterface() || java.lang.reflect.Modifier.isAbstract(c.getModifiers())) {
+            throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Cannot allocate " + c);
+          }
           return (T) newInstance.invoke(null, c, Object.class);
         }
       };
```

## Summary

The bug was that the UnsafeAllocator would try to allocate instances of interfaces and abstract classes using various mechanisms (like sun.misc.Unsafe), even though these cannot be meaningfully instantiated. The fix adds validation in all three allocation implementations to check if the class is an interface or abstract class using `c.isInterface()` and `java.lang.reflect.Modifier.isAbstract(c.getModifiers())` before attempting allocation, and throws an `UnsupportedOperationException` appropriately.

This ensures that:
1. Interface instantiation correctly throws `UnsupportedOperationException`
2. Abstract class instantiation correctly throws `UnsupportedOperationException`  
3. Concrete class instantiation continues to work as expected

All tests now pass, including the triggering test `testInterfaceInstantiation` and related tests.

